<!doctype html>
<html lang="en" class="no-js">
	<head>
		<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
		<script src="../js/modernizr.js"></script>
		<script src="../js/jquery.js"></script>
		<script src="../js/jquery-menu.js"></script>
		<script src="../js/main.js"></script>
		<title>Trains of Ruegen</title>
		<meta charset="UTF-8" />
	</head>
	<body>
		<header>
			<div class="cd-dropdown-wrapper">
				<a class="cd-dropdown-trigger" href="#0"> Menu </a>
				<nav class="cd-dropdown">
					<h2>Menu</h2>
					<a href="#0" class="cd-close"> Close </a>
					<ul class="cd-dropdown-content">
						<li>
							<a href="index.html"> Index </a>
						</li>
						<li>
							<a href="info.html"> Helpful Information </a>
						</li>
					</ul>
				</nav>
			</div>
		</header>
		<main class="cd-main-content">
			<nav class="navbar">
				<aside>
					<h2 class="center">Content</h2>
					<ol id="table-of-contents" style="list-style: none; padding: 0;"></ol>
				</aside>
			</nav>
			<script>
				document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", () => {
					const toc = document.getElementById("table-of-contents");
					if (!toc) return;
					const articles = document.querySelectorAll("article[id] h2");
					const fragment = document.createDocumentFragment();
					articles.forEach((heading) => {
						const article = heading.closest("article");
						if (!article) return;
						const id = article.id;
						const listItem = document.createElement("li");
						const link = document.createElement("a");
						link.href = `#${id}`;
						link.textContent = heading.textContent;
						link.setAttribute("aria-label", `Jump to ${heading.textContent}`);
						listItem.appendChild(link);
						fragment.appendChild(listItem);
					});
					toc.appendChild(fragment);
				});
			</script>
			<section>
				<h1>Historical</h1>
				<p>WIP.hist</p>
			</section>
			<section>
				<h1>Narrow Gauge</h1>
				<article id="putb">
					<h2>Putbus</h2>
					<p>
						Putbus is a small town on the island of Ruegen with about 4,000
						residents. The Putbus train station is located in the center of the
						town and is served by the Ruegensche Kleinbahn, a narrow-gauge
						railway that connects Putbus with Binz, Goehren, and Lauterbach. The
						station building is a listed building and was built in 1899.
					</p>
					<h1>Standard Gauge</h1>
					<article id="sass">
						<h2>Sassnitz</h2>
						<p>
							Sassnitz is the white harbor town by the sea, it has about 10,000
							residents, with that, it is the second-largest city. She owns a
							port where until 2000 the "Stenaline" a ferry to Trelleborg
							(Sweden) was departing. From this port, freight trains were
							shipped to the USSR during the GDR era.
						</p>
					</article>
					<article id="lanc">
						<h2>Lancken</h2>
						<p>
							Lancken is a part of Sassnitz. This station is only equipped for
							the essentials, such as an intercom system, a timetable, and a
							shelter. In addition, there is a track to the chalk mine.
						</p>
					</article>
					<article id="saga">
						<h2>Sagard</h2>
						<p>
							Sagard is a small town with 2,460 residents. Her train station
							looks more modern than Lancken's.
						</p>
					</article>
					<article id="binz">
						<h2>Ostseebad Binz</h2>
						<p>
							The Ostseebad Binz train station is the main train station of the
							popular seaside resort Binz on the island of Ruegen. It was opened
							on May 15, 1939. The reception building dates back to 1938 and is
							still in operation today. The station has three platform tracks
							and is accessible for people with disabilities. It is regularly
							served by regional and long-distance trains, offering connections
							to cities such as Berlin, Hamburg, and Munich. The central
							location of the station allows travelers to reach the town center,
							the pier, and the fine sandy beach within a few minutes on foot.
							In addition, there is a connection to public transportation and
							taxis at the station, making it easy to continue traveling within
							Binz and beyond.
						</p>
					</article>
					<article id="liet">
						<h2>Lietzow (Ruegen)</h2>
						<p>
							The Lietzow (Ruegen) train station was opened in 1891 as a stop on
							the Stralsund–Sassnitz railway line and is located on the southern
							edge of Lietzow. Since 1939, the railway line to Binz branches off
							here, making Lietzow an important transfer point on the island of
							Ruegen. In 2009/10, an extensive renovation of the station took
							place, during which the number of main tracks was reduced to four.
							Today, the station is served by regional trains of the Ostdeutsche
							Eisenbahn GmbH (ODEG), which offer connections between Rostock,
							Stralsund, Sassnitz, and Binz. However, there is always a shuttle
							train that goes to the other stop.
						</p>
					</article>
					<article id="berg">
						<h2>Bergen(Ruegen)</h2>
						<p>
							Bergen is the district town of Ruegen and is the most populous
							city on Ruegen. It is one of the central traffic hubs of the
							island of Ruegen. It has facilities such as bicycle parking,
							parking spaces, and taxis. The DB Travel Center offers personal
							consultation and ticket sales.
						</p>
					</article>
					<article id="tesc">
						<h2>Teschenhagen</h2>
						<p>
							The Teschenhagen station is located in the municipality of Sehlen
							on the island of Ruegen and was opened on July 1, 1883. It is
							located on the Stralsund–Sassnitz railway line and has two tracks
							with corresponding platforms. Originally designed as a train
							station with freight traffic, Teschenhagen now serves as a stop
							for regional trains of the Ostdeutsche Eisenbahn GmbH (ODEG),
							which offer connections between Rostock, Stralsund, and Sassnitz
							or Binz. The historic reception building is still intact and was
							partially inhabited until mid-2022.
						</p>
					</article>
					<article id="samt">
						<h2>Samtens</h2>
						<p>
							The Samtens train station is located on the outskirts of the
							eponymous municipality on Ruegen. It is also located on the
							Stralsund–Sassnitz railway line and is served by regional trains
							of the ODEG. After the expansion of the Electronic Signal Box
							(ESTW) from Altefaehr to Bergen, the station is unstaffed. The
							platforms were modernized, with the main platform being renovated
							and a new outer platform towards Bergen being constructed.
						</p>
					</article>
					<article id="ramb">
						<h2>Rambin (Ruegen)</h2>
						<p>
							The Rambin (Ruegen) station was opened on July 1, 1883, on the
							Stralsund–Sassnitz railway line and is located on the outskirts of
							the municipality of Rambin. It has two tracks with corresponding
							platforms and is also served by regional trains of the ODEG, which
							offer hourly connections between Rostock, Stralsund, and the
							seaside resorts of the island of Ruegen. The historic reception
							building is still present, but no longer in operation.
						</p>
					</article>
					<article id="alte">
						<h2>Altefaehr</h2>
						<p>
							The Altefaehr train station is located about one kilometer
							southeast of the center of Altefaehr on the island of Ruegen, just
							around 200 meters from the Strelasund. It was opened on July 1,
							1883, and is located on the Stralsund–Sassnitz railway line.
							Before the construction of the Ruegen Causeway in the 1930s,
							Altefaehr was only accessible by ferry; the original station was
							then located closer to the ferry terminal. Today, regional express
							trains of the Ostdeutsche Eisenbahn GmbH (ODEG) stop here every
							two hours on the route from Rostock via Stralsund to Sassnitz or
							Binz. The central location of the station allows travelers to
							reach the town center and the waterfront promenade on foot in just
							a few minutes.
						</p>
					</article>
					<article id="rueg">
						<h2>Stralsund Ruegendamm</h2>
						<p>
							The Stralsund station Ruegendamm, also known as Ruegendamm
							Station, was opened on October 5, 1936, and is located on the
							Stralsund–Sassnitz railway line. It is located a few meters before
							the Ziegelgraben Bridge, which connects Stralsund with the island
							of Ruegen. The station has a partially covered central platform
							and is served by regional trains of the ODEG, which offer
							connections between Rostock, Stralsund, and Sassnitz or Binz.
							Parking is available in front of the station, and there is a
							connection to public transportation. A ticket counter or other
							service facilities are not available, however.
						</p>
					</article>
